file=Shared OS/logical/mckee-story-structure.md · h=name: mckee-story-structure\ntype: logical (Route D — practitioner-operator wisdom)\nstatus: extracted 2026-07-16\nsource_books:\n- McKee, Robert, *Story: Substance, Structure, Style, and the\nPrinciples of Screenwriting* (HarperCollins, 1997).\nISBN: 978-0060391683.\nAuthor: Robert McKee — the most sought-after screenwriting\nlecturer in the world; students include 65 Academy Award\nwinners, 250 Emmy winners.\nChapters used: Introduction (Story Is About Principles),\nPart 1 (The Writer and the Art of Story), Part 2 (The Elements\nof Story — Ch.3: Structure and Setting, Ch.4: Structure and\nGenre, Ch.5: Structure and Character, Ch.6: Structure and\nMeaning), Part 3 (The Principles of Story Design — Ch.7: The\nSubstance of Story, Ch.8: The Inciting Incident, Ch.9: Act\nDesign, Ch.10: Scene Design, Ch.11: Scene Analysis, Ch.12:\nComposition, Ch.13: Crisis, Climax, Resolution), Part 4 (The\nWriter at Work — Ch.14: The Principle of Antagonism, Ch.15:\nExposition, Ch.16: Problems and Solutions).\n\n- Campbell, Joseph, *The Hero with a Thousand Faces* (1949).\nPublic domain. https://archive.org/details/herowiththousand00camp\nAuthor: Joseph Campbell — Sarah Lawrence professor.\nKey concept: the monomyth / Hero's Journey (17 stages).\n\nsource_urls:\n- Books/Robert McKee - Story (pdf).pdf\n- https://archive.org/details/herowiththousand00camp (Campbell)\n\nassigned_agents: weave, lena\nextended_skills: narrative-design, coherence-qa\nportable: true\ncross_references:\n- storyline_engine.py (5-part structure validator, gap detector,\nSB7 checker, tension curve estimator)\n- heath-made-to-stick.md (Stories principle — McKee provides\nthe deep structure; Heath provides the application layer)\n- berger-contagious.md (Stories as Trojan Horse — Berger's\nstory-brand integration rule)\n- marketing_laws.py (Campbell's Hero's Journey — the monomyth\nis the deepest narrative structure law)\n · in:=Robert McKee's *Story* (1997) is the definitive treatise on narrative design. McKee argues that story is not a genre-dependent formula but a set of universal principles that govern how human beings experience meaning. His central thesis: **"Story is about principles, not rules. A rule says, 'You must do it this way.' A principle says, 'This works ... and has through all remembered time.'"** (Introduction, p.3)\n\nThis extraction bridges McKee's screenwriting architecture into narrative frameworks for Brand Studio — every brand story, campaign narrative, and content arc should pass through McKee's structural gate before production.\n\n · ### 1.1 The Controlling Idea=*Ch.6, pp.110-132*\n\n> "A Controlling Idea may be expressed in a single sentence describing how and why life undergoes change from one condition of existence at the beginning to another at the end." (Ch.6, p.115)\n\nMcKee's Controlling Idea is the thematic spine of any story — the irreducible truth the story demonstrates through action. It has two components:\n\n**Value + Cause:** "The story's climactic value (positive or negative) caused by the protagonist's final action."\n\nExamples from McKee (Ch.6, pp.118-125):\n- *Dirty Harry:* "Justice prevails because the protagonist is more violent than the criminals." (Value: Justice; Cause: superior violence)\n- *Groundhog Day:* "Happiness fills our lives when we learn to love unconditionally." (Value: Happiness; Cause: unconditional love)\n- *The Verdict:* "Justice prevails because the protagonist is willing to sacrifice his own self-interest for truth." (Value: Justice; Cause: self-sacrifice)\n\n**For Brand Studio stories:** Every brand narrative must have a Controlling Idea. Without it, the story has no thematic unity — it's a sequence of events but not a story. A brand film about "innovation" without a Controlling Idea is a montage. With a Controlling Idea ("Human progress happens when individuals refuse to accept limits," e.g., Apple's "Think Different"), it becomes a narrative.\n · ### 1.2 Character Desire + Antagonism=*Ch.5, pp.90-109; Ch.14, pp.310-333*\n\n> "A character is, at core, a choice-maker under pressure. The deeper the pressure, the truer the choice, and the more the choice reveals character." (Ch.5, p.101)\n\nMcKee's character model has three dimensions:\n\n**1. Conscious Desire (Ch.5, pp.92-95):** What the character WANTS. The external goal. Luke Skywalker wants to destroy the Death Star. The protagonist of a brand story wants the product to solve their problem.\n\n**2. Unconscious Desire (Ch.5, pp.95-98):** What the character NEEDS. The internal, often unrecognized, yearning. Luke Skywalker needs to become a Jedi — but doesn't consciously know this when the story begins. The customer doesn't need a drill — they need a hole; they don't need a car — they need freedom.\n\n**3. The Antagonism Principle (Ch.14, pp.310-322):** "A protagonist and their story can only be as intellectually fascinating and emotionally compelling as the forces of antagonism make them." The antagonist is not necessarily a villain — it is the sum total of all forces opposing the protagonist's desire. McKee's "Negation of the Negation" principle: the antagonist must progress from Contradictory (the opposite of the positive value) to Contrary (a lesser negative) to the Negation of the Negation (the double-negative — a negative disguised as a positive, which is MORE dangerous).\n\n**The Negation of the Negation applied to brand storytelling (Ch.14, pp.318-322):**\n · tb=\| Positive Value \| Contrary \| Contradictory \| Negation of the Negation \| · tb=\|---------------\|----------\|--------------\|--------------------------\| · tb=\| Love \| Indifference \| Hate \| **Hate masquerading as Love** (smothering, controlling "love") \| · tb=\| Truth \| White lies \| Deception \| **Self-deception** (believing your own lies) \| · tb=\| Justice \| Unfairness \| Injustice \| **Injustice legitimized as Justice** (corrupt system) \| · tb=\| Freedom \| Restriction \| Slavery \| **Slavery perceived as Freedom** (addiction, ideology) \| · ### 1.2 Character Desire + Antagonism=**For Brand Studio:** The antagonist in a brand story should not be a competitor. The antagonist should be the Negation of the Negation — the false solution the customer has been sold, the self-deception they've accepted, the "good enough" that is actually the enemy of better. Nike's antagonist is not Adidas — it's the inner voice that says "you can't."\n\n · p2—:PART 2 — THE 5-PART DRAMATIC STRUCTURE=*Ch.8-13, pp.163-307*\n\nMcKee's most famous structural contribution is the five-part dramatic spine, which maps onto the classic three-act structure but provides richer detail.\n · ### 2.1 The Inciting Incident=*Ch.8, pp.163-185*\n\n> "The Inciting Incident radically upsets the balance of forces in the protagonist's life." (Ch.8, p.169)\n\nThe Inciting Incident must:\n1. **Happen to the protagonist** — not be passively observed. McKee (Ch.8, p.172): "The protagonist must react to the Inciting Incident."\n2. **Radically upset the balance** — the world BEFORE the incident is in equilibrium. After, it is not. Irreversibly.\n3. **Raise the Major Dramatic Question** — the question the audience will hold until the climax. Will the protagonist achieve their desire?\n4. **Occur at the right moment** — McKee (Ch.8, p.178): "Bring in the Central Plot's Inciting Incident as soon as possible ... but not until the moment is ripe." Too early: audience doesn't care. Too late: audience is bored.\n\n**Brand application:** The Inciting Incident in a brand narrative is the problem that disrupts the customer's equilibrium. Before: everything was fine (stasis). After: the problem emerges (inciting incident). The product is the guide that helps the protagonist navigate the disrupted world.\n · ### 2.2 Progressive Complications=*Ch.9, pp.186-207*\n\n> "The second element of the five-part design is Progressive Complications: a series of events that makes the protagonist's pursuit of desire increasingly difficult." (Ch.9, p.189)\n\nMcKee's key insight: **complications must progress in difficulty and depth.** Each complication must be harder than the last. The antagonist's forces intensify. The stakes rise.\n\n**The Gap Principle (Ch.7, pp.145-160):**\n\n> "The Gap is the difference between expectation and result. The protagonist takes an action, expecting a particular result. The result is something else entirely — opening a gap between what was expected and what happened. The protagonist's next action must bridge this gap."\n\nMcKee (Ch.7, p.150): "Story is born in the Gap." The Gap is where drama lives. A scene without a Gap — where the protagonist acts and gets exactly the expected result — is not a scene; it's an exposition. Every turning point in a narrative is a Gap: the protagonist's expectation is violated, forcing adaptation.\n\n**Brand application:** The Gap principle is the mechanism for demonstrating product value. Before: customer expects solution X to work. Gap: X fails, or creates a new problem. Bridge: your product/service. The bigger the gap between expectation and result, the more dramatic and memorable the brand story.\n · ### 2.3 Crisis=*Ch.13, pp.278-290*\n\n> "The Crisis is the story's Obligatory Scene. It is the moment of greatest tension, when the protagonist faces the most powerful forces of antagonism and must make a decision from which there is no turning back." (Ch.13, p.280)\n\nMcKee distinguishes Crisis from Climax:\n- **Crisis = the DECISION.** The protagonist stands at a crossroads where two (or more) irreconcilable goods, or the lesser of two evils, must be chosen. McKee (Ch.13, p.283): "True choice is dilemma."\n- **Climax = the ACTION that flows from the decision.**\n\nThe Crisis is the "obligatory scene" — the scene the audience has been waiting for since the Inciting Incident. It is the promise the story made to the audience at the beginning.\n\n**Brand application:** The Crisis in a brand narrative is the moment the customer must choose between the old way (failing, painful, inadequate) and the new way (your solution). The more genuine the dilemma — the more real the cost of change vs. the cost of staying — the more powerful the narrative.\n · ### 2.4 Climax=*Ch.13, pp.291-300*\n\n> "The Climax is the story's ultimate reversal. From the Crisis decision, the protagonist acts — and the world is irrevocably changed." (Ch.13, p.292)\n\nMcKee's rules for the Climax:\n1. **It MUST answer the Major Dramatic Question.** McKee (Ch.13, p.294): "All story telling is a promise. The Inciting Incident raises the Major Dramatic Question; the Climax answers it."\n2. **It MUST be the absolute climax.** No scene can carry more emotional weight. If the Climax happens on page 90 and there are 30 more pages, the structure is broken.\n3. **It MUST produce a Value Change.** The story began with a certain charge of value (e.g., negative: injustice). The climax reverses that charge (positive: justice) or negates it utterly (the negation of the negation: injustice triumphant).\n · ### 2.5 Resolution=*Ch.13, pp.301-307*\n\n> "The Resolution, the fifth element of the five-part structure, is the aftermath of the Climax. It closes the story's open threads and shows the new equilibrium." (Ch.13, p.303)\n\nThe Resolution serves three purposes:\n1. **Show the new balance** — the world after the climax is different. The resolution establishes the new normal.\n2. **Close subplots** — secondary character arcs are resolved.\n3. **Provide emotional closure** — the audience needs a moment to process the climax's impact.\n\nMcKee warns (Ch.13, p.305): "The Resolution must be brief. The longer the resolution, the more the audience's emotional experience of the climax dissipates. A resolution that goes on too long is an author who can't let go."\n\n**Brand application:** The Resolution in a brand narrative is the "after" picture — the customer using the product, life improved, the new normal established. Testimonials, case studies, and product demos are structural Resolutions.\n\n · p3—:PART 3 — SCENE DESIGN=*Ch.10, pp.208-233*\n · ### 3.1 The Scene as the Fundamental Unit=> "A scene is a story in miniature — an action through conflict in a unity of time and space that turns the value-charged condition of a character's life." (Ch.10, p.211)\n\nEvery scene, McKee argues, must contain:\n1. **A Turning Point** — the value at stake (love/hate, freedom/slavery, truth/lie) changes charge within the scene.\n2. **A Value Change** — the scene opens with one charge (+ or -) and closes with the opposite.\n3. **Conflict** — the character wants something and faces opposition in getting it.\n4. **A Gap** — expectation vs. result. The character acts expecting X; Y happens instead.\n\n**The "No Scene" test (Ch.10, pp.215-218):** McKee's brutal diagnostic for weak scenes. If a scene does not contain a turning point — if the value does not change charge — it is not a scene. It is an "expository interlude" and should be cut or restructured. "If a scene does not turn, it is not a scene."\n · ### 3.2 Act Design=*Ch.9, pp.186-207*\n\nMcKee (Ch.9, p.195): "An act is a series of scenes that culminates in a major reversal — a turning point greater than any preceding scene." The classic three acts:\n · tb=\| Act \| Function \| Turning Point \| · tb=\|-----\|---------\|---------------\| · tb=\| **Act One** \| Setup + Inciting Incident \| The protagonist commits to the pursuit of desire. No turning back. \| · tb=\| **Act Two** \| Progressive Complications \| The protagonist hits a wall. The old approach fails. A new approach is needed. (Often the "darkest moment.") \| · tb=\| **Act Three** \| Crisis + Climax + Resolution \| The final choice is made. The world is irrevocably changed. \| · p4—:PART 4 — THE GAP PRINCIPLE (Extended)=*Ch.7, pp.145-162*\n\nMcKee's Gap Principle is the engine of all dramatic action, and it maps directly onto the brand storytelling challenge.\n\n**McKee's model (Ch.7, pp.148-155):**\n1. Protagonist has a **Desire** (conscious want).\n2. Protagonist takes an **Action** to achieve the desire.\n3. The world **reacts** — and the reaction is NOT what the protagonist expected.\n4. A **Gap** opens between expectation and result.\n5. The protagonist must choose a **new action** to bridge the gap.\n6. **Repeat** — each cycle escalates stakes, deepens character, and surprises the audience.\n\n**The Gap in brand storytelling:**\n- Customer's expectation: "The generic/competitor/DIY solution will work."\n- Gap: "It didn't work. Or it created a new problem. Or it was adequate but not transformative."\n- Bridge: Your product/service closes the gap in a way the customer couldn't have predicted.\n- New expectation: Life is better with your solution.\n- New gap (for ongoing narrative): Even with your solution, new challenges emerge — and your brand evolves.\n\n**Connection to Berger (STEPPS — Stories, Ch.6):** "The Gap is why people tell stories. If everything goes as expected, there is no story. The Gap IS the story."\n\n · p5—:PART 5 — CAMPBELL'S HERO'S JOURNEY (The Monomyth)=*Campbell, The Hero with a Thousand Faces (1949), public domain*\n\nMcKee's structural principles share deep roots with Joseph Campbell's monomyth, the archetypal narrative pattern Campbell identified across world mythologies. While McKee focuses on the mechanics of storytelling, Campbell provides the archetypal shape that underlies all effective stories.\n · ### The 17 Stages of the Monomyth (Campbell, 1949)=**Departure:**\n1. The Call to Adventure\n2. Refusal of the Call\n3. Supernatural Aid (Meeting the Mentor)\n4. The Crossing of the First Threshold\n5. The Belly of the Whale\n\n**Initiation:**\n6. The Road of Trials\n7. The Meeting with the Goddess\n8. Woman as the Temptress\n9. Atonement with the Father\n10. Apotheosis\n11. The Ultimate Boon\n\n**Return:**\n12. Refusal of the Return\n13. The Magic Flight\n14. Rescue from Without\n15. The Crossing of the Return Threshold\n16. Master of Two Worlds\n17. Freedom to Live\n · tb=\| Campbell (Hero's Journey) \| McKee (5-Part Structure) \| Brand Narrative \| · tb=\|--------------------------\|------------------------\|-----------------\| · tb=\| Call to Adventure \| Inciting Incident \| Problem awareness \| · tb=\| Refusal of the Call \| Internal conflict (unconscious desire vs. conscious desire) \| Skepticism about solutions \| · tb=\| Meeting the Mentor \| New information/guide character \| Brand as the guide \| · tb=\| Crossing the Threshold \| First major complication \| First engagement with brand \| · tb=\| Road of Trials \| Progressive Complications \| Customer journey touchpoints \| · tb=\| The Ultimate Boon \| Climax \| Transformation achieved \| · tb=\| Return with the Elixir \| Resolution \| Customer becomes advocate \| · ### The 5-Part Structure Validator=For every brand narrative, check the 5-part structure:\n · tb=\| # \| Element \| Check \| · tb=\|---\|---------\|-------\| · tb=\| 1 \| **Inciting Incident** \| Is there a clear moment that disrupts the protagonist's equilibrium? \| · tb=\| 2 \| **Progressive Complications** \| Do obstacles escalate in difficulty? Does each complication raise stakes? \| · tb=\| 3 \| **Crisis** \| Is there a genuine dilemma — a choice between two irreconcilable goods or lesser evils? \| · tb=\| 4 \| **Climax** \| Does the climactic action answer the Major Dramatic Question? Is it the peak of emotional intensity? \| · tb=\| 5 \| **Resolution** \| Is the new equilibrium shown? Is the audience given emotional closure? \| · ### The Scene Value-Change Detector=For every scene (video segment, ad beat, content block), check:\n- **Opening value charge:** At the start of this unit, is the value at stake positive (+) or negative (-)?\n- **Closing value charge:** At the end, has it flipped?\n- **If no flip:** This is not a scene — it's exposition. Cut it or restructure it.\n · ### The Gap Detector=For every turning point:\n- What was the protagonist's expected result?\n- What actually happened?\n- Is there a meaningful gap between them?\n- Does the gap force a new, more difficult choice?\n · ### The Character-Desire-Antagonism Triangle=For every brand narrative:\n- **Protagonist:** The customer. Not the brand.\n- **Conscious Desire:** What the customer WANTS (the surface problem).\n- **Unconscious Desire:** What the customer NEEDS (the deeper truth).\n- **Antagonism:** NOT the competitor. The true opponent — the internal limit, the false solution, the systemic problem.\n- **Guide:** The brand. The brand helps the protagonist bridge the gap but does NOT replace the protagonist.\n\n · tb=\| McKee \| Heath (Stories, Ch.6) \| Integration \| · tb=\|-------\|----------------------\|-------------\| · tb=\| 5-Part Structure \| Three Story Archetypes (Challenge, Connection, Creativity) \| McKee provides the structural deep dive; Heath provides the accessible application layer \| · tb=\| Gap Principle \| Mental Flight Simulator \| The Gap IS what the audience mentally rehearses — "what would I do in that gap?" \| · tb=\| Controlling Idea \| Simple (Commander's Intent) \| The Controlling Idea IS the Commander's Intent of the story \| · tb=\| McKee \| Miller (StoryBrand) \| Integration \| · tb=\|-------\|---------------------\|-------------\| · tb=\| Protagonist's Desire \| Character (SB7 #1) \| Both start with the protagonist \| · tb=\| Antagonism \| Problem (SB7 #2) \| McKee's antagonist = Miller's external + internal + philosophical problem \| · tb=\| Guide character \| Guide (SB7 #3) \| The guide who helps the protagonist \| · tb=\| Progressive Complications \| Plan + Call to Action (SB7 #4-5) \| Complications make the plan necessary \| · tb=\| Crisis + Climax \| Failure Stakes + Success (SB7 #6-7) \| What's at stake in the crisis; what the climax achieves \| · tb=\| McKee \| Berger (Stories, Ch.6) \| Integration \| · tb=\|-------\|----------------------\|-------------\| · tb=\| Gap Principle \| Story-Brand Integration Rule \| The Gap IS where the brand must be essential to the story \| · tb=\| Controlling Idea \| Practical Value (Ch.5) \| The Controlling Idea carries the practical value of the story \| · tb=\| 5-Part Structure \| Trojan Horse \| The structure IS the horse that carries the idea \| · bwo:BOUNDARIES WITH OTHER SCRIPTS=- **storyline_engine.py:** Implements the 5-part structure validator, Gap detector, Character-Desire-Antagonism triangle checker, scene value-change detector, and tension curve estimator from this extraction.\n- **heath-made-to-stick.md:** Heath's Stories principle (Ch.6) is the "why" of storytelling; McKee provides the "how." SUCCESs scores narrative effectiveness; McKee diagnoses narrative structure.\n- **berger-contagious.md:** Berger's Stories as Trojan Horse maps onto McKee's Controlling Idea — the horse (story structure) must carry the soldiers (brand message) without being about the soldiers.\n- **marketing_laws.py:** Campbell's Hero's Journey (law_hero_journey placeholder) is the archetypal pattern underlying McKee's structural principles.\n